14 MODIFY SAFEKEEPING STATUTE RELATED TO WILLS
15 SECTION 10.(a) G.S. 31-11 reads as rewritten:
16 "§ 31-11. Depositories in offices of clerks of superior court where living persons may file
17 deposit wills.
18 (a) The clerk of the superior court in each county of North Carolina is required to keep a
19 receptacle or depository in which any testator who desires to do so may deposit that testator's
20 original paper will for safekeeping. The clerk is only authorized to receive the will from the
21 testator, or an a testator's agent with sufficient authority under a power of attorney instrument to
22 deposit the will, or an attorney for the testator. Once a testator has died, the clerk is not authorized
23 to receive the will for the clerk's receptacle or depository from any agent or attorney for the
24 testator.
25 (b) The clerk shall, upon written request of the testator, or the duly authorized a testator's
26 agent with sufficient authority under a power of attorney instrument to withdraw the will, or
27 attorney for the testator, permit said will or testament to be withdrawn from said depository or
28 receptacle at any time prior to the death of the testator.
29 (c) While in the clerk's receptacle or depository, the contents of said will shall not be
30 made public or open to the inspection of anyone other than the testator or the testator's duly
31 authorized agent or attorney testator, a testator's agent with sufficient authority under a power of
32 attorney instrument to review and inspect the will, or an attorney for the testator until the testator
33 has died. Once the clerk has received proof of the testator's death, the clerk is authorized to allow
34 the will to be made open to the inspection of any person interested in the testator's estate. The
35 will shall remain in the clerk's receptacle or depository until the will is offered for probate.probate
36 or filed with the clerk without probate.
37 (d) The clerk is required to retain the original paper will until withdrawn, probated or
38 filed in the deceased testator's estate file, or once 60 years have passed since the will was
39 originally deposited with the clerk. If after 60 years the will has not been withdrawn or filed in
40 the deceased testator's estate file, the clerk is authorized to comply with records retention rules
41 for deposited wills set by the Director of the Administrative Office of the Courts."
42 SECTION 10.(b) This section becomes effective October 1, 2026.
