21 CLARIFY JURY COMMISSION APPOINTMENTS
22 SECTION 14.(a) G.S. 9-1 reads as rewritten:
23 "§ 9-1. Jury commission in each county; membership; selection; oath; terms; expenses of
24 jury system.
25 Not later than July 1, 1967, there shall be appointed in each county a jury commission of
26 three members. One member of the commission shall be appointed by the senior regular resident
27 superior court judge, one member by the clerk of superior court, and one member by the board
28 of county commissioners. The appointees shall be qualified voters of the county, and shall serve
29 for terms of two years. Appointees may be reappointed to successive terms. If an appointment is
30 not made by September 1, the incumbent shall serve for an additional two-year term. A vacancy
31 in the commission shall be filled in the same manner as the original appointment, for the
32 unexpired term. Each commissioner shall take an oath or affirmation that, without favor or
33 prejudice, he will honestly perform the duties of a member of the jury commission during his
34 term of service. The compensation of commissioners shall be fixed by the board of county
35 commissioners, and shall be paid from the general fund of the county. All expenses necessary to
36 carry out the provisions of this Chapter and to administer the jury system, including all data
37 processing, document processing, supplies, postage, and other similar expenses, except as
38 otherwise provided in this Chapter, shall be paid from the general fund of the county, except that
39 the clerk of superior court shall furnish clerical or other personnel assistance, as the commission
40 may reasonably require."
41 SECTION 14.(b) G.S. 9-2(a) reads as rewritten:
42 "(a) It shall be the duty of the jury commission during every odd-numbered year to prepare
43 a master list of prospective jurors qualified under this Chapter to serve in the biennium beginning
44 on January 1 of the next year. Instead of providing a master list for an entire biennium, the
45 commission may prepare a master list each year if the senior regular resident superior court judge
46 requests in writing that it do so. In either event, the master list shall be completed no later than
47 November 15."
48 SECTION 14.(c) G.S. 20-43.4(a) reads as rewritten:
49 "(a) The Commissioner of Motor Vehicles shall provide to each county jury commission
50 an alphabetical list of all persons that the Commissioner has determined are residents of the
51 county, who will be 18 years of age or older as of the first day of January of the following year,
